<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910726-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>910726-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- La Quinta Motor Inns Inc.:   Firm Posts 2nd-Period Loss,   Takes Extraordinary Charges</HL><DATE>07/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LQM LQP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)LODGING, HOTELS, MOTELS, LODGES, CAMPGROUNDS (LOD)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   La Quinta Motor Inns Inc. posted a net loss of $2.1million, or 16 cents a share, for the second quarter,including $6.8 million in one-time charges related to itsrecent tussle with large shareholders and its efforts toimprove shareholder value.   The company said the results also include a $463,000extraordinary charge for refinancing debt. La Quinta had netincome of $2.6 million, or 20 cents a share, in theyear-earlier period.</LP><TEXT>   Revenue increased 7.9% to $65 million from $60.2 million.   The hotel chain, which is based in San Antonio, Texas,said that the special charges included a $2.5 millionwrite-down of assets, such as computer software. Theremaining cash charges included the cost of hiring McKinsey andamp;Co. to study operating efficiencies; expenses related todismissing 72 employees, including 50 at its headquarters;hiring investment bankers to explore the possible sale of thecompany, and costs related to a threatened proxy fight by agroup including the Bass family of Fort Worth.   La Quinta said that average occupancy fell to 69.8% in thequarter from 70% a year ago, but said its average room rateincreased to $43.13 from $41.07 last year.</TEXT></DOC>